excerpt: In addition to its gold stupa, pagodas & museum, this mountainside temple offers broad city views.
detail_description: Wat Phra That Doi Suthep, a revered temple in Northern Thailand, is known for its gold stupa, pagodas, and museum. Perched on a mountainside, the temple offers stunning panoramic views of the city. To explore off-the-beaten-path routes in the region, consider hiring a local trekking guide through a reputable company. This allows access to non-touristic areas and an authentic experience.
name: Wat Phra That Doi Suthep
address: Tambon Su Thep, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50200, Thailand

excerpt: 14th-century Buddhist temple boasting gold & copper Buddhas, murals & ancient manuscripts.
detail_description: Wat Phra Singh Woramahawihan is a revered 14th-century Buddhist temple located in Chiang Mai, Thailand. It is home to gold and copper Buddhas, ancient manuscripts, and intricate murals. The temple's main attraction is the Phra Phutta Sihing Buddha statue, which holds great cultural significance and is paraded through the city during the Songkran Festival.
name: Wat Phra Singh Woramahawihan
address: 2 Samlarn Rd, Tambon Si Phum, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50200, Thailand

excerpt: Temple complex with a partially crumbled 15th-century chedi & a pillar believed to protect the city.
detail_description: Wat Chedi Luang Varaviharn is a captivating temple complex nestled in the heart of Chiang Mai's Old City. This historical site features a partially crumbled chedi dating back to the 15th century, which stands as a testament to the city's rich cultural heritage. Visitors are drawn not only by its architectural grandeur but also by the pillar believed to offer protection to the city.
name: Watchediluang Varaviharn
address: 103 Prapokklao Road, Tambon Si Phum, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50200, Thailand

excerpt: Elephant rehabilitation facility offering intimate visitor experiences such as feeding & bathing.
detail_description: Located approximately 60 km from Chiang Mai city, Elephant Nature Park is a renowned sanctuary and rescue center for distressed elephants in Thailand. Founded by elephant conservationist Lek Chailert, the park aims to rehabilitate and provide a safe haven for these majestic animals. Visitors have the opportunity to engage in intimate experiences such as feeding and bathing the elephants, as well as participating in volunteer programs.
name: Elephant Nature Park Office
address: 1 Ratchamanka Rd, Phra Sing, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50100, Thailand

excerpt: Known as a site for many community events, this preserved city gate dates back to ancient times.
detail_description: Tha Phae Gate, a well-preserved city gate with a rich history dating back to the Lanna Kingdom, was originally known as Chiang Ruak Gate. Situated by the Mae Ping River, it served as a vital entrance for trade routes. The gate's name was changed to Tha Phae, meaning 'Harbor of the Floating House,' reflecting its connection to river traders and fishermen. Today, it stands as an iconic landmark within the ancient city wall of Chiang Mai.
name: Tha Phae Gate
address: Tha Phae Road, Chang Khlan Sub-district, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50200, Thailand

excerpt: Vibrant, 3-floor market featuring fresh produce, street food, casual clothing & household goods.
detail_description: Warorot Market, also known as Kad Luang, is a bustling 3-floor market in Chiang Mai that offers an array of experiences for visitors. The market is a paradise for food enthusiasts, with its wide selection of fresh produce, local snacks, and ready-to-eat meals. Additionally, the market features affordable clothing, fashion accessories, and household goods. It's a great place to immerse yourself in the local way of life and explore the vibrant atmosphere.
name: Warorot Market (Kad Luang)
address: 10,12, 14 Wichayanon Rd, Chang Moi Sub-district, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50300, Thailand

excerpt: Large zoo with many animal species, day & evening tram safari rides, kids' activities & shows.
detail_description: Chiang Mai Night Safari is a large zoo offering day and evening tram safari rides, kids' activities, and shows. The park features three major animal zones: Predator Prowl, Savanna Safari, and Jaguar Trail. Visitors can enjoy petting tiger cubs, hand-feeding wild animals, and watching dancing fountains and laser light shows. The Savanna Night Safari allows guests to see kangaroos, white rhinos, and water buffalos from an open tram.
name: Chiang Mai Night Safari
address: 33, Nong Kwai, Hang Dong District, Chiang Mai 50230, Thailand

excerpt: Bustling night market featuring street food vendors & local crafts, plus souvenirs.
detail_description: Chiang Mai Night Bazaar is a lively market in Thailand's northern capital, offering a wide array of experiences. The historic center is surrounded by monasteries and temples, with accommodations ranging from traditional homes to modern city hotels. The night bazaar, open from 18:00 to 22:30 daily, features an extensive collection of stalls and shops selling local crafts, souvenirs, street food, clothing, electronics and more.
name: Chiang Mai Night Bazaar
address: Changklan Rd, Chang Moi Sub-district, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50100, Thailand

excerpt: Museum in a former courthouse with cultural artifacts, textiles & ceramics, plus a small cafe.
detail_description: The Lanna Folklife Museum is housed in a former courthouse, now a colonial-style building, and offers an insightful journey into the local way of life and history. The museum showcases cultural artifacts, textiles, ceramics, and art pieces that represent the region's rich heritage. With descriptions available in both Thai and English, visitors can explore exhibits on Lanna Buddhist worship, mural paintings, lacquerware, pottery, architectural styles, and traditional cloth weaving.
name: Lanna Folklife Centre
address: QXQQ+X87, Prapokklao Road, Si Phum, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50200, Thailand

excerpt: Sizable zoo & aquarium with a snow dome, panda exhibit & kids’ water park, plus animal feedings.
detail_description: Nestled in the foothills of the Doi Suthep Mountains, Chiang Mai Zoo is a sprawling 200-acre wildlife haven that's home to over 400 animal species. This family-friendly destination offers a diverse range of attractions, including a snow dome, panda exhibit, kids' water park, and animal feedings.
name: Chiang Mai Zoo
address: 100 Huay Kaew Rd, Tambon Su Thep, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50200, Thailand

excerpt: 13th-century temple with a gold chedi offering ancient Buddha & elephant statues on scenic grounds.
detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Chiang Mai's historic old town, Wat Chiang Man stands as a testament to the city's rich heritage, being its oldest temple dating back to the late 13th century. This enchanting site features a stunning gold chedi and an array of impressive elephant statues that showcase remarkable craftsmanship. Visitors are drawn not only by the ancient pagoda but also by the serene library known as Ubosot, which serves as a vital space for ceremonies.
name: Wat Chiang Man
address: 171 Ratchapakhinai Rd, Tambon Si Phum, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50200, Thailand

excerpt: Buddhist temple in tranquil surrounds with a golden dome, ornate interior & historic mausoleum.
detail_description: Wat Suan Dok, also known as the "Field of Flowers Temple," is a tranquil Buddhist temple located about 1 km west of Chiang Mai's old city. The temple was established in the late 14th century on the grounds of a former royal flower garden. One of its most striking features is the impressive 48-meter-high bell-shaped chedi that enshrines sacred relics from Sukhothai.
name: Wat Suan Dok
address: 139 Suthep Rd, Tambon Su Thep, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50200, Thailand

excerpt: Chiang Mai is a city in mountainous northern Thailand. Founded in 1296, it was capital of the independent Lanna Kingdom until 1558. Its Old City area still retains vestiges of walls and moats from its history as a cultural and religious center. It’s also home to hundreds of elaborate Buddhist temples, including 14th-century Wat Phra Singh and 15th-century Wat Chedi Luang, adorned with carved serpents.
detail_description: Nestled in the picturesque mountains of northern Thailand, Chiang Mai is a city steeped in rich history and culture. Established in 1296, it served as the capital of the Lanna Kingdom until 1558. The Old City area still showcases remnants of its past, with ancient walls and moats that speak to its significance as a cultural hub.
name: Chiang Mai
address: Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai, Thailand

excerpt: 5,499-foot mountain featuring trails through evergreen forests & a picturesque, hilltop temple.
detail_description: Doi Suthep is a 5,499-foot mountain in Chiang Mai, Thailand, known for its picturesque trails through evergreen forests and a hilltop temple called Wat Phra That Doi Suthep. The temple, coated in gold and nearly 800 years old, offers stunning views of the city below. It's a popular tourist spot, so visiting in the morning is recommended to avoid crowds.
name: Doi Suthep
address: Suthep, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50200, Thailand

excerpt: Forested national park featuring a Buddhist temple, Bhubing Palace, wildlife, waterfalls & more.
detail_description: Doi Suthep-Pui National Park is a forested sanctuary in Chiang Mai Province, Thailand, known for its natural beauty and cultural landmarks. The park encompasses two mountains, Doi Suthep and Doi Pui, and is home to the revered Wat Phra That Doi Suthep temple. Visitors can climb 309 steps to reach the temple complex and enjoy panoramic views of Chiang Mai.
name: Doi Suthep-Pui National Park
address: RW48+RC4, Sriwichai Alley, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50200, Thailand

excerpt: Tours are available of these brick ruins of an ancient city & temple in serene surrounds.
detail_description: Wiang Kum Kam is an ancient city and temple complex located just 5 kilometers southeast of the Old City in Chiang Mai, Thailand. This historic settlement was the capital of the Lanna Kingdom, built in the 13th century under King Mangrai the Great. Today, Wiang Kum Kam serves as an open-space museum showcasing Lanna culture from that period. Visitors can explore brick ruins, Buddhist sculptures, and everyday items from this era.
name: Wiang Kum Kam
address: 149 หมู่ที่ 2 Somphot Chiang Mai 700 Pi Rd, Tha Wang Tan, Saraphi District, Chiang Mai 50100, Thailand

excerpt: This laid-back venue presents a regular lineup of live jazz artists in a casual space.
detail_description: The North Gate Jazz Co-Op in Chiang Mai is a laid-back venue that offers live jazz performances in a casual setting. It has become an institution over the years, attracting both local and visiting musicians for jam sessions. The cozy shophouse interior and outdoor tables create a bohemian atmosphere where patrons can enjoy drinks while soaking up the lively music.
name: The North Gate Jazz Co-Op
address: 91/1-2 ถนน, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50200, Thailand

excerpt: Small, statue-rich Buddhist temple & monastery hidden in a woodland & reached via a hiking trail.
detail_description: Nestled in the serene foothills of Doi Suthep, Wat Pha Lat is a hidden gem that often escapes the notice of travelers rushing to the more famous Wat Phra That Doi Suthep. This charming Buddhist temple and monastery may not boast the grandeur of some other temples in Chiang Mai, but its true beauty lies in its tranquil woodland setting. Accessible via a scenic hiking trail, visitors are greeted by lush greenery and soothing sounds from nearby waterfalls.
name: Wat Pha Lat
address: บ้านห้วยผาลาด 101, Sriwichai Alley, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50200, Thailand

excerpt: Temple atop a forested mountain featuring ornate gold carvings & a 17-m. sitting Buddha statue.
detail_description: Nestled atop a lush, forested hill on the outskirts of Chiang Mai lies Wat Phra That Doi Kham, also known as the Golden Temple. This hidden gem is celebrated for its magnificent 17-meter seated Buddha statue, which gleams in white and gold. With roots tracing back over a millennium, this temple offers visitors an enchanting experience filled with intricate shrines and pagodas to explore amidst the serene backdrop of the Doi Suthep Mountain range.
name: Wat Phrathat Doi Kham
address: Mae Hia, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50100, Thailand

excerpt: This ornate, Lanna-style Buddhist temple was originally built during the Mangrai dynasty.
detail_description: Nestled in the vibrant "Silver District" of Chiang Mai, Wat Sri Suphan, affectionately known as the Silver Temple, is a stunning example of Lanna-style architecture. Originally constructed during the Mangrai dynasty, this temple may not be vast in size but captivates visitors with its intricate hand-crafted silver decorations that shimmer brilliantly under the sun. As you approach Wat Sri Suphan, you're welcomed by an enchanting display of silver artistry that truly lives up to its name.
name: วัดศรีสุพรรณ(พระอุโบสถเงิน)
address: 100 Wua Lai Rd, Haiya Sub-district, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50100, Thailand

excerpt: Landscaped grounds featuring flowers, plants & sculptures, plus an elegant commemorative chapel.
detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Chiang Mai, Royal Park Rajapruek is a breathtaking botanical garden that invites visitors to immerse themselves in nature's splendor. Spanning approximately 200 acres, this expansive park features meticulously landscaped grounds adorned with over 1,900 species of plants and flowers. Each themed zone showcases unique aspects of Thai culture and horticulture, including the enchanting Thai Tropical Garden and the vibrant Orchid Garden.
name: Royal Park Rajapruek
address: 334, Mae Hia, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50100, Thailand

excerpt: Seasonal waterfall with a short walking trail in a picturesque, natural setting.
detail_description: Huai Kaeo Waterfall is a seasonal attraction located near Chiang Mai, offering smaller cascades and plenty of hiking trails. The area features picturesque natural scenery with easy access to the waterfall, although it may not be wheelchair or stroller accessible past a certain point. Visitors can enjoy the serene pools below the falls for picnicking and relaxation, as well as embark on an interesting jungle hike starting from the waterfall area.
name: Huay Keaw Waterfall
address: Suthep, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50300, Thailand

detail_description: The Asia Scenic Thai Cooking School is a highly regarded cooking school that offers both full- and half-day courses. One of the highlights is a visit to a local market where participants can select fresh ingredients for their dishes. The full-day course includes a trip to the farm, where an instructor provides a tour of the garden and educates on various fresh ingredients used in Thai cuisine. The instructor's explanations about dish preparation and cooking techniques are thorough, making the experience enjoyable and educational.
name: Asia Scenic Thai Cooking School
address: Rachadamneon Rd, PraPokKlao Soi 5, Muang, Chiang Mai 50200, Thailand

excerpt: Bustling open-air market with a wide range of food stalls serving street eats, sweets & produce.
detail_description: Chiang Mai Gate Market is a lively open-air market located on the southern side of the old city wall in Chiang Mai. During the day, it offers a wide variety of street food snacks, grilled seafood, and fresh produce. As night falls, the market transforms as street vendors set up tents and prepare for a bustling evening. The area is also known for its local fruit and vegetable market during the day.
name: Chiang Mai Gate Market
address: Bumrung Buri Rd, Tambon Phra Sing, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50200, Thailand

detail_description: Wat Umong is a serene and spiritual temple located just outside the city, offering a refreshing change from the bustling urban attractions. Nestled in the forest, this temple provides a tranquil atmosphere for visitors to explore. One of its unique features is the ancient tunnels beneath the weathered stupa, adding an intriguing element to its charm. The temple's peaceful surroundings make it an ideal place for Vipassana meditation and chanting with monks, providing a serene retreat from the city's hustle and bustle.
name: Wat Umong
address: Tambon Su Thep, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50200, Thailand

excerpt: Intricate teak Buddhist temple with gilded accents & colorful mosaics, founded in the 14th century.
detail_description: Wat Phantao is a hidden gem nestled in the heart of Chiang Mai, showcasing the rich history and artistry of Lanna architecture. Founded in the 14th century, this intricate teak Buddhist temple captivates visitors with its stunning gilded accents and colorful mosaics. While it may not be as expansive as some neighboring temples, its charm lies in the exquisite details found within its centuries-old teakwood structures.
name: Wat Phantao
address: ตําบล พระสิงห์, 105 Prapokklao Road, Tambon Si Phum, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50200, Thailand

excerpt: Buddhist temple dating to at least the 1300s & featuring a prominent chedi (stratified tower).
detail_description: Nestled just outside the bustling gates of Chiang Mai's old city, Wat Lok Moli is a captivating Buddhist temple that dates back to at least the 1300s. Unlike most temples that face east, this unique site aligns along a north-south axis, adding to its charm. The highlight here is its striking chedi, one of the tallest in the area, which houses the ashes of several kings from the Mengrai dynasty.
name: Wat Lok Moli
address: 298/1 Manee Nopparat Rd, ตำบล ศรีภูมิ อำเภอ เมืองเชียงใหม่, Chiang Mai 50200, Thailand

excerpt: Elegant royal residence on stilts with a notable rose garden, open to the public most of the year.
detail_description: Bhubing Palace, situated about 13.6 miles from Chiang Mai's city center near Wat Phra That Doi Suthep temple, is a stunning royal residence built in the traditional northern Thai architectural style known as Reun Mu. This elegant palace, constructed in 1961, serves as the winter residence for the Thai Royal Family during their visits to Chiang Mai and also functions as a guest house for distinguished foreign visitors.
name: Bhubing Palace
address: 1 หมู่ที่ 12 Sriwichai Alley, Suthep, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50200, Thailand

excerpt: Bustling, colorful Sunday night market for local produce, prepared foods, crafts & souvenirs.
detail_description: Chiang Mai's Sunday Night Market, also known as the Walking Market, is a vibrant and bustling event that takes place every Sunday along Ratchadamnoen Road starting at Thapae Gate. The market features a wide array of local produce, prepared foods, crafts, and souvenirs. Visitors can explore handmade goods while witnessing artisans crafting their wares right at their stalls.
name: Chiang Mai Night Market
address: Rachadamnoen Rd, Tambon Si Phum, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50200, Thailand

excerpt: Organization offering a range of tours highlighting a range of Thai cultural experiences.
detail_description: Embark on a cultural journey with the Mae Ping River Cruise, a popular choice for those seeking an authentic Thai experience in Chiang Mai. The two-hour boat trip along the Mae Ping River offers ever-changing scenery, from traditional teak houses to rural greenery. After a 45-minute sail, visitors stop at a local farmer's house for lunch and get to witness the production of jasmine rice while enjoying the lush gardens.
name: Mae Ping River Cruise
address: ท่าน้ำวัดชัยมงคล, 133 Charoen Prathet Rd, Tambon Chang Khlan, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50100, Thailand

excerpt: Elephant sanctuary offering overnight visits, with activities such as bathing & jungle walks.
detail_description: The Elephant Jungle Sanctuary is a compassionate haven for elephants located just outside Chiang Mai. Visitors can partake in various activities such as feeding, bathing, and walking with the elephants. The sanctuary offers morning and afternoon programs that provide insight into the lives of these majestic creatures. By choosing to visit this sanctuary, guests contribute to the rehabilitation and well-being of formerly captive elephants. Many visitors describe their experiences as unforgettable, highlighting activities like mud baths and river walks alongside these gentle giants.
name: Elephant Jungle Sanctuary (Office)
address: 119/10 Tha Phae Road, Chang Khlan Sub-district, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50100, Thailand

excerpt: The walled, moated Old City is Chiang Mai’s cultural heart, with centuries-old temple compounds like Wat Phra Singh, known for its Lion Buddha statue, and Wat Chedi Luang, with a huge reconstructed pagoda. The lively Sunday Walking Street market features handicraft stalls and street performers. Restaurants offer casual Thai eats and Western-style food, while street stalls serve fried noodles and fresh fruit shakes.
detail_description: Chiang Mai's Old City is a historic and cultural hub, enclosed by a moat and filled with ancient temples like Wat Phra Singh and Wat Chedi Luang. The area hosts the vibrant Sunday Walking Street market, offering local handicrafts and street performances. Visitors can enjoy a variety of dining options from casual Thai eateries to Western-style restaurants, as well as street vendors selling fried noodles and fresh fruit shakes.
name: Old City
address: Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai, Thailand

excerpt: Retail shops, cafes & food stalls share space in a modern marketplace with big windows & a hip vibe.
detail_description: One Nimman is a modern marketplace located in Chiang Mai, offering a vibrant mix of retail shops, cafes, and food stalls. The first floor and the third and fourth floors house an arts, culture, and lifestyle living space that seamlessly blends modern architecture with local Chiang Mai culture. Lets Relax Chiang Mai One Nimman provides a serene spa experience within this lively environment. The complex also features European architectural influences that perfectly complement its myriad of shops, restaurants, cafes, and art galleries.
name: One Nimman
address: 1-1, One, 1-5 Nimmanahaeminda Road, เมือง Chiang Mai 50200, Thailand

excerpt: Outdoor bazaar with vendors selling traditional street snacks, handmade crafts & souvenirs.
detail_description: Wua Lai Walking Street is a vibrant outdoor bazaar that spans about a mile and takes place every Saturday evening on Wualai Road near the Silver Temple. It offers an array of traditional street snacks, handmade crafts, souvenirs, and local delicacies. The market is known for its bustling atmosphere and diverse offerings including handcrafted lamps, dolls, soaps, jewelry, clothes, original paintings, and locally designed jewelry.
name: Wua Lai Walking Street Saturday Market
address: 69 Wua Lai Rd, Haiya Sub-district, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50100, Thailand

excerpt: A large seating area anchors this bustling night bazaar with street food, gifts, beer & live music.
detail_description: Ploen Ruedee Night Market is a vibrant and lively destination in Chiang Mai that promises an unforgettable evening for food lovers and entertainment seekers alike. This bustling night bazaar features a spacious seating area where visitors can indulge in an array of street food, from traditional Thai dishes to international flavors. Adventurous eaters might even try some local delicacies like fried insects! The atmosphere is enhanced by live music performances, creating the perfect backdrop for enjoying delicious meals with friends or family.
name: Ploen Ruedee Night Market
address: 28/3-4 Changklan Rd, Tambon Chang Moi, เมือง, Chiang Mai 50100, Thailand

excerpt: Historic Buddhist temple complex with woods, a small lake, ancient tunnels & practicing monks.
detail_description: Nestled just outside the bustling old town of Chiang Mai, Wat Umong Suan Putthatham is a captivating historic temple complex that transports visitors back to the 13th century. This enchanting site features a network of ancient tunnels adorned with intriguing cave paintings and serene Buddha statues, all set against a backdrop of lush greenery and a tranquil lake. The atmosphere here is peaceful, making it an ideal spot for meditation or simply soaking in the natural beauty surrounding you.
name: Wat Umong Suan Putthatham
address: 135, Suthep, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50200, Thailand

excerpt: Sculpture of Kings Mengrai, Ramkamhaeng and Ngam Muang, purported founding fathers of Chiang Mai.
detail_description: The Three Kings Monument, located in the heart of Chiang Mai's old-walled city, pays tribute to the founding fathers of the Lanna Kingdom. This elegant monument and its surrounding courtyard are considered the symbolic center of modern Chiang Mai. The sculpture depicts Kings Mengrai, Ramkamhaeng, and Ngam Muang, who played significant roles in establishing the city.
name: Three Kings Monument
address: QXRP+3WX, Prapokklao Road, Tambon Si Phum, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50200, Thailand

excerpt: Sizable park with a contemporary playground, picnic areas, shade trees & water features.
detail_description: Nong Buak Haad Public Park is a popular and sizable park located in the historic city of Chiang Mai. It offers a contemporary playground, picnic areas, shade trees, and water features. The park's three large ponds are surrounded by paths and bridges, making it an ideal spot for leisurely walks. Additionally, visitors can enjoy amenities such as a children's playground, basketball courts, and a coffee shop within this green space.
name: Buak Hard Public Park
address: Arak Rd, Tambon Phra Sing, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50200, Thailand

excerpt: Regal cultural museum featuring historical & artistic exhibits to preserve local heritage.
detail_description: Chiang Mai City Arts & Cultural Center is a must-visit museum that showcases the rich history and art of the city. Housed in the former Chiang Mai City Hall, it features 15 exhibition rooms spanning over 700 years of history, from the early settlements along the Ping River to the Lanna Kingdom and modern Chiang Mai. The center also offers cultural performances, a market for authentic souvenirs, and an option for a traditional Khantoke Dinner experience.
name: Chiang Mai City Arts & Cultural Centre
address: Prapokklao Road, Tambon Si Phum, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50200, Thailand

detail_description: A lot of Thai: Home cooking class in Chiang Mai is a standout choice for those looking to learn the art of Thai cooking. The class offers a delightful setting and uses top-quality ingredients, but what truly sets it apart is Yui and her husband Kwan. They not only teach iconic Thai dishes with ease but also provide valuable insights into the chemistry and physics of cooking, life philosophy, and numerous cooking tips that extend beyond just Thai cuisine.
name: A lot of Thai : Home Cooking Class
address: Soi9, 165 Chiang Mai-Lamphun Rd, Nong Hoi Sub-district, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50000, Thailand

excerpt: Bustling indoor marketplace with an eclectic range of clothing stores, food stalls & gift shops.
detail_description: The night market at Chiang Mai University is a lively and eclectic place where you can find a wide range of clothing stores, food stalls, and gift shops. It's especially popular with students, who can often find great deals on clothing and accessories. If you're on a budget, this is the place to go!
name: Chiang Mai University Night Market
address: ซอย สุเทพ, Tambon Chang Phueak, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50300, Thailand

Visitors can interact with the artwork, feeling as though they are part of the scenes depicted. Founded by Mr. Jang Kyu Suk from South Korea, this gallery features works by 10 professional Korean painters. The realistic and interactive nature of the paintings allows visitors to immerse themselves in various scenarios such as flying on a magic carpet or exploring the ocean depths.
name: The Meeting Room Art Gallery

name: Sunday Night Market
address: QXQP+8GH, Rachadamnoen Rd, Tambon Si Phum, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50200, Thailand

excerpt: Those born in the year of the snake journey to this unique, historical Buddhist temple with artwork.
detail_description: Nestled away from the bustling city life, Wat Jed Yod, also known as the Temple of Seven Spires, offers a tranquil escape into history and spirituality. Located just a short drive from the Old City of Chiang Mai, this hidden gem is surrounded by lush fields and serene streets that lead you through picturesque landscapes framed by the majestic Suthep mountain range.
name: Wat Jed Yot, Phra Aram Luang
address: 90, Chang Phueak, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50300, Thailand

excerpt: Hillside village set in a lush national park, home to a Hmong tribe, who sell traditional crafts.
detail_description: Nestled in the lush national park of Doi Pui mountain, Hmong Doi Pui Village is a hillside settlement inhabited by the Hmong tribe. The village provides a glimpse into the traditional lifestyle, folk culture, and livelihood practices of the Hmong people. Visitors can explore traditional Hmong-style homes, witness villagers wearing their distinctive clothing, and purchase authentic Hmong handicrafts from local stalls.
name: Hmong Doi Pui Village
address: หมู่ที่ 11 อุทยานแห่งชาติดอยสุเทพ-ปุย, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50200, Thailand

excerpt: Weekday market with a covered section selling flowers, produce & household goods.
detail_description: Ton Lam Yai Market is a vibrant and bustling market located in Chiang Mai, specializing in flowers. It is situated next to the larger Worarat Market along the quiet River Ping. The market operates 24 hours a day, making it convenient for visitors to explore. In the morning, visitors can witness the arrival of fresh deliveries while avoiding the heat and traffic later in the day. The market offers an array of colorful blooms, attracting locals and tourists alike.
name: Ton Lam Yai Market
address: 88/1 Wichayanon Rd, Chang Moi Sub-district, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50300, Thailand

excerpt: Each Sunday afternoon until midnight this street becomes a gallery for local arts & crafts.
detail_description: Tha Phae Walking Street is a vibrant market in Chiang Mai that comes alive every Sunday afternoon until midnight. The area showcases local arts and crafts, offering a mix of traditional handicrafts and tourist souvenirs. As the evening sets in, the street becomes bustling with people enjoying the lively atmosphere filled with music from street buskers. Visitors can explore an array of products including handbags, t-shirts, postcards, and picture frames while also indulging in delicious Northern Thai street food.
name: Tha Phae Walking Street
address: Rachadamnoen Rd, Tambon Si Phum, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50200, Thailand

excerpt: Small Buddhist temple with traditional Lanna architecture, once the site of the sacred city pillar.
detail_description: Wat Inthakhin Sadue Muang, also known as the 'temple of the city navel,' is a small Buddhist temple in Chiang Mai with traditional Lanna architecture. It was once home to the sacred city pillar called Sao Inthakin. The temple's viharn houses the revered Buddha image Luang Pho Khao and features intricate woodwork and gold structures.

excerpt: Simple, tranquil Buddhist temple with a pond, ornate carvings & a storied history.
detail_description: Wat Jet Lin is a serene Buddhist temple in Chiang Mai, known for its tranquil atmosphere and rich history. The temple's name originates from the seven water channels used by the Lanna Royal family for bathing. While the exact construction date remains uncertain, it is believed to have origins dating back to the early 16th century. The main prayer hall houses various Buddha statues, including a striking large golden Buddha and a smaller jade statue.
name: Wat Jetlin
address: Prapokklao Road, Phra Sing, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50200, Thailand

excerpt: Museum with indoor/outdoor exhibits on the history & culture of Northern Thailand's mountain tribes.
detail_description: The Highland People Discovery Museum, also known as Chiang Mai's Tribal Museum, is a cultural museum located in Rama IX Lanna Park. It was established in 2017 and showcases the history and culture of the mountain tribes of Northern Thailand.
name: The Highland People Discovery Museum
address: Rama IX Lanna Park, Chotana Rd, Chang Phueak, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50300, Thailand
